products.description: The Nike Air Flare is mostly recognizable as they were worn on-foot by Andre Agassi in 1994 en route to winning his second Grand Slam championship. They feature a built-in inner bootie as well as visible Max Air in the heel.
The Nike Air Tech Challenge 2 was designed by Tinker Hatfield and originally released from 1989-90. They were retroed for the first time in 2008 and then again from 2013-15.

The Nike Air Tech Challenge 3 was originally released in 1990. They were retroed for the first time in 2007, but without the signature Tennis Ball logo on the back heels. When they returned in 2015, they came back remastered with original detailing.

The Nike Air Tech Challenge 4 (IV) debuted in 1991 as Andre Agassi's fourth signature shoe with Nike. The performance tennis sneaker featured a Visible Max Air Unit in the heel along with a Dynamic Fit, Durathane, airbrush-inspired accents, and a Swoosh-less Nike branded upper. In true Agassi style, the sneaker released in several bright colorways.

The Nike Air Tech Challenge Huarache was originally released in 1992 and worn on the tennis court by Andre Agassi. Combining Huarache technology with the Tech Challenge line, they feature Neoprene bootie, polyurethane midsole and visible Air sole unit in the heel. They were retroed for the first time in 2014.
The Nike Air Tech Challenge Hybrid combines elements from the Tech Challenge 1, 3 and 4 throughout the upper, and is finished off by Tech Challenge 2 tooling.

The original Nike Air Force 1 High debuted in 1982 as the first performance basketball sneaker to feature Nike Air. Over the decades since its introduction, the timeless silhouette has lent its look to several Air Force 1 spin-off models which includes the Nike Air Force 1 Boot line. The AF1 Boot line includes the Air Force 1 Duckboot, the Air Force 1 DCN Military Boot, and the Nike Air Force 1 Boot.

The Bruce Kilgore designed Nike Air Force 1 High debuted in 1982 as the first performance Basketball sneaker to feature Nike Air. The sneaker features a high-top cut, an ankle strap, and a large volume midsole that houses the enclosed Nike Air unit. While the sneaker is no longer used for performance basketball, it is Nike's most iconic and popular design.

The Bruce Kilgore designed Nike Air Force 1 High debuted in 1982 as the first performance basketball sneaker to feature Nike Air. The sneaker was discontinued in 1984 and re-released in 1986. Originally designed to exist as a high-top model only, the 1986 Nike Air Force 1 re-release introduced the Nike Air Force 1 Low. Today, the Nike Air Force 1 Low is Nike's most popular and best-selling sneaker.

The original Bruce Kilgore designed Nike Air Force 1 High debuted in 1982 as the first performance basketball sneaker to feature Nike Air. The Nike Air Force 1 Mid debuted decades later as lifestyle option to the original performance designed high-top.

The Nike Air Force 1 Ultra Flyknit debuted in 2016 as a Flyknit upgraded Air Force 1. The sneaker is 50% lighter than the original Air Force 1 and features a combination of Flyknit and leather on the upper.

The Nike Lunar Force 1 Boot debuted in 2014 as a more ruggedized and weather-ready option for the fall/winter. The boot borrows from the Lunar Force 1 High featuring the same overall look and feel with added waterproof or weatherproof materials and a boot-like rugged outsole. The Lunar Force 1 Boot line includes the Lunar Force 1 Duckboot and Lunar Force 1 Sneakerboot.

The debut signature sneaker of Utah Jazz star guard Donovan Mitchell, the Adidas D.O.N. Issue #1 (Determination Over Negativity) takes on a numbering system inspired by Mitchell's Spida nickname and love for comic books.The low - top model features mesh construction with a lace - up closure, a padded collar, foam midsole and rubber outsole for traction.

The Adidas D.O.N. Issue #2, the second signature sneaker for NBA All-Star Donovan Mitchell, features an engineered mesh upper that provides improved lateral support through a webbed lacing system, which sits atop a Bounce midsole to support explosive movements on the hardwood.
Inspired by the Pro Model, the adidas Futurestar Boost combines cues from the Pro Model with Boost cushioning and a reinforced shell toebox. They were released in 2015.

The adidas Crazy 8 was originally released in 1997 as the KB8. Their name was changed when they were retroed for the first time in 2007 due to Kobe no longer being with the brand. The sneaker features air mesh lining, an inner bootie construction, EVA midsole and Torsion system plate. Since their first retro, they have been re-relased numerous times in various colorways.

Portland Trail Blazers superstar, Damian Lillard, debuts his fourth signature sneaker. The Dame 4 is built in mid-top construction in white mesh and a looped lacing system. It features a gum outsole with Bounce cushioning and an aggressive, jagged midsole with personal touches on the heel YKWTII ' which means You Know What Time It Is. Release date is October 6, 2017 at a retail price of $115.
The JS Prime Skin was designed by Jeremy Scott. A take on the adidas Feet You Wear concept, this pair features a shrouded upper with elements of the Top Ten 2000. They were released in 2014.

The adidas D Lillard 1 was the first signature sneaker for Damian Lillard. They made their debut in 2015 and designed by Robbie Fuller. Coming in low-top, the sneaker features a TECHFIT tongue and inner bootie and adiprene+ cushioning.

The Stan Smith is one of the most iconic adidas sneakers of all-time. A tennis sneaker originally released as the Haillet in 1964, they were renamed the Stan Smith after adidas signed the tennis legend to an endorsement deal in the 1970s. Since then, they have been re-released numerous times in various styles and versions.

Damian Lillard draws inspiration from his childhood with the release of the adidas D Lillard 2 Inspired by Lillard and his friends playing games on a tennis court near his grandma’s house in Brookfield, the sneaker features a felt-like upper done in a fluorescent tennis ball yellow sitting on a matching Bounce sole. Dame also wore this pair during his Dame Dolla concert. Release date is Aug. 30, 2016 exclusively at the Foot Locker flagship location in New York City. Retail price is $105.
The Adidas Stan Smith sports a clean white leather upper with contrasting green accents on the heel tab and tongue while perforated Three Stripes branding is seen on the sides.

A multi-collaboration between streetwear giants Alife in New York and Starcow in Paris. Both shops bring forth a minimalistic approach with a two shoe pack in the adidas Gazelle and Stan Smith. The Stan Smith features an all white leather upper with Alife and Starcow logos embossed as well as on the tongue tab. American and French flag embroideries are on the medial heel. Release date is July 29, 2017 at a retail price of $150.

The Ozweego 2 is a re-designed version of the classic adidas Ozweego. Designed by Raf Simons, they made their debut in 2015. The sneaker features a woven textile liner, transparent silicone windows and and adiWear rubber outsole.

The adidas J Wall 1 was the first signature sneaker for John Wall after making the switch from Reebok to adidas. They were released from 2014-15 and feature an air mesh textile upper, full length lateral FITFRAME, a full length adiprene+ cushioned midsole and Wall's logo on the tongue.

The most popular Shawn Kemp signature sneaker, the Kamikaze 2 was the Reignman's second signature sneaker with Reebok. Originally released in 1995, they feature a counterblocked upper, infinity Polyurethane midsole and molded sockliner with Hexalite and Ultra Hexalite cushioning. They were retroed for the first time in 2013 and have been re-released in numerous versions and colorways since.

The BBC ICECREAM x Reebok BB4600 High that's releasing exclusively at ComplexCon sports an all-over embroidered red and blue Diamond & Dollar print throughout the black-based leather upper, which sits atop a contrasting white midsole. Release date is Nov. 2, 2019.

Part of the BBC ICECREAM x Reebok collection that will only be available at the 2019 ComplexCon in Long Beach is a low-top version of the iconic BB4600 featuring a soft suede upper in an tonal ICECREAM yellow colorway. Release date is Nov. 2, 2019.

Released in 2014, the Reebok Answer 14 continued Allen Iverson's signature Basketball sneaker line with Reebok. The sneaker was designed by Jeremy Sallee and is inspired by the Reebok Answer 3 and featured DMX technology.
The Reebok Aztrek silhouette made its original run in the early '90s. The uppers feature mesh and suede panels on the upper embedded with Hexalite cushioning atop a Diamond Stud rubber outsole.

products.shoeName: BBC ICECREAM X Reebok Answer V
products.description: Dropping exclusively at ComplexCon, this BBC ICECREAM x Reebok Answer V is a fitting nod to the fact that both Pharrell Williams and Allen Iverson are from Virginia Beach in a multi-colored iteration of the sneaker. Release date is Nov. 2, 2019.

The Reebok Classic debuted in 1983 as a performance running sneaker and has since gone on to become one of the most popular Reebok models of all-time. Though the sneaker is no longer used for running, it has become a popular canvas for collaborations and lifestyle colors.

The Reebok Phase 1 debuted in 1985 as part of Reebok's original tennis shoe lineup. The sneaker was billed as the first all-leather shoe that did not require any break-in time. Reebok offered a 21 day try-out of the Phase 1, promising to both return the purchaser's money and send a can of tennis balls if they were not completely satisfied with their purchase. Although it is no longer used for tennis performance, the sneaker has become the preferred canvas for many collaborations.

The Instapump Fury is one of the most popular Reeboks of all-time. The first running sneaker to feature Pump technology, they were originally released in 1994. They feature Pump CO2 technology in the form of an inflatable cage on the upper, a carbon fiber shank plate and Hexalite cushioning. The Instapump Fury has been retroed numerous times in various styles, versions and colorways.

The Reebok Twilight Zone Pump was originally released in 1990 and were worn on-court by Dominique Wilkins. The high-top sneaker features Pump technology on the tongue and ERS cushioning. They have been retroed numerous times in various styles and colorways.

The Shaq Attaq 1 was originally released in 1992 and was the first signature sneaker for Shaquille O'Neal from Reebok. They featured a leather and suede upper with Pump technology on the tongue and Graphlite. They were retroed for the first time in 2013, shortly after Shaq returned to the brand.

The Shaqnosis was originally released in 1995 and was the fifth signature sneaker for Shaquille O'Neal from Reebok. They feature a nubuck and leather upper with Hexalite cushioning in the heel and forefoot. They were retroed for the first time in 2013, shortly after Shaq returned to the brand.

products.description: The Reebok Alien Stomper debuted in 1986 as an exclusive design for Sigourney Weaver a.k.a Ellen Ripley in the movie Aliens. The sneaker finally hit retail shelves 30 years later in 2016.
The Puma Dreamer 2 is J. Cole's second signature shoe with Puma. It features a mid-top upper and is equipped with the brand's RS technology made to be worn off and on the basketball court.

Rapper J. Cole's first signature basketball sneaker with Puma dubbed the RS-Dreamer will debut in 2020 and is created with the intent of being worn both on and off the court. It features a knitted upper that's paired with a dynamic lacing system for lockdown. Puma's ProFoam tech is used on the midsole for lightweight cushioning while the rubber outsole provides maximum grip.

products.shoeName: Nintendo X Puma RS-Dreamer Super Mario 64
products.description: In collaboration with Nintendo to celebrate the 35th anniversary of Super Mario 64 video game, this Puma RS-Dreamer sports a red-based color scheme with blue accents that are inspired by Mario's outfit. Release date is Sept. 4, 2020 at a retail price of $125.

Dubbed Ebony and Ivory, this iteration of J. Cole's Puma RS-Dreamer wears a simple white-based mesh upper that's paired with black overlays, which sits atop a white ProFoam midsole and a translucent outsole. Release date is Dec. 4, 2020 at a retail price of $125.

J. Cole's Puma RS-Dreamer will make its retail debut in a stealthy black-based knit upper that's combined with premium suede overlays, which sits atop a multicolored ProFoam midsole for lightweight cushioning and energy return. Release date is July 31, 2020 at a retail price of $125.

The Blaze Of Glory made its debut in 1993. They feature a lace closure, perforated detailing, Trinomic cushioning, EVA midsole and rubber outsole. They have been re-released numerous times in various colorways.

Inspired by the Puma Clyde, the Clyde Court takes cues from the past and revamps it with a mesh material on the upper and the classic formstripe on the lateral and medial sides. Additional details include Puma branding on the tongue and heel, which sits atop a semi-translucent tooling.

The Puma Court Rider is the latest installment to the brand's Rider franchise. The shoe boasts a mesh upper paired with a dynamic lacing system surrounding the forefoot for enhanced stability and support. The shoe’s signature design elements are attributed to the tooling with the full-length Rider foam midsole along with a high abrasion rubber outsole.
Co-designed by both NBA champion Kyle Kuzma and founder of streetwear label Rhude, Rhuigi Villaseñor, the Puma Clyde All-Pro Kuzma Mid boasts a mid-cut upper including Kuzma’s logo in the sock liner.

products.shoeName: Puma Creeper X Fenty By Rihanna
products.description: The Puma Creeper x Fenty by Rihanna is a product of Rihanna and Puma's collaborative partnership. The sneaker features the upper from the Puma Suede with a platform sole.
A design from the '80s, the Puma Fast Rider redefined typical running shoes 40 years ago with its super-light design and aggressive, shock-absorbing outsole.

This iteration of the '80s-inspired Puma Fast Rider boasts a black-based nylon upper that's paired with a black Formstrip branding along with an orange Riderfoam midsole and a grippy Federbein outsole for all-day comfort.
